ξ 3. The lex lulia maiestatis was passed by Julius Caesar, Cic. Philipp. t. 9. Previously the law ol treason had tested partly on usage (Livy 1. 26), partly on the Twelve Tables (Dig. 48. 4. 3. pr), and a lex Cornelia (Cic. in Pis. 21, pro Cluent. 35). The intention to commit the offence was punished no less than its execution (moliti sunt): ‘qui cogitaverit ....eadem enim severitate voluntatem sceleris, qua effectum, puniri iura voluerunt’ Cod. 9. 8. 5. Perhaps the same rule was observed in all crimes, ‘in maleficiis voluntas spectatur, non exitus’ Dig. ad leg. Corn. de sicariis 48.8.14. The lex lulia had substituted a perpetual aquae et ignis interdictio for the older punishment ol death, Paul. sent. rec. 5. 29. 1 ; but the latter was re-established as early as Tiberius, Tac. Ann. 6. 18, Suetonius, Tiberius 58 sq.
